---
description: Conventional Commit and pull-request conventions for this repository
alwaysApply: true
---

When writing a git commit message or a pull request, follow `AGENTS.md` at the
repository root.

- Read `git diff --staged` — the staged diff is the source of truth, not filenames.
- Choose an accurate Conventional Commit type and scope; write an imperative subject
  (≤ 50 chars ideally, 72 hard; no trailing period).
- Add a body only when it explains *why* the change was made, not *how*.
- Notate breaking changes with `!` and/or a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer.
- Add trailers when relevant and true: `Closes #123`, `Co-authored-by:`, `Signed-off-by:`.
- If nothing is staged, say so and stop — never `git add -A`. If asked to choose what to
  stage, select only the files that form one coherent commit, not everything at once.
- For a pull request (only when asked), detect the base branch (main/master), read the
  branch's diff against it, and write a title plus a description with summary, what
  changed, testing, and breaking changes, as plain Markdown.
- Never mutate git on your own: propose the exact `git add` / `git commit` / PR commands
  and run them only when explicitly asked; commit the staged set as-is.
- Never add AI attribution to a commit or PR unless the user explicitly asks.

See `AGENTS.md` for the complete workflow, type taxonomy, and examples.
